# CODEOWNERS — required reviewers for trstctl (TEST-006)
#
# GitHub requests a review from the listed owner(s) on any PR that touches a
# matching path, and — when "Require review from Code Owners" is enabled in branch
# protection (see docs/branch-protection.md) — a PR cannot merge without their
# approval. The last matching pattern wins, so the security-critical blocks at the
# bottom override the catch-all above.
#
# This file is the in-repo, reviewable record of *who must sign off on what*. The
# audit (TEST-006) flagged that ownership of the root-of-trust paths was not
# codified; codifying it here makes the gate provable from the artifact, and
# docs/codeowners_test.go asserts every security-critical path below stays covered.
#
# Owner: @ctlplne/security is the maintainer team for these paths (the ctlplne org
# is now the canonical namespace — the same one used for the module path, container
# images, and clone URLs). This team must exist on GitHub — create @ctlplne/security
# and add the maintainer(s) — or CODEOWNERS will not resolve to a valid reviewer.
# The coverage test only requires that each critical path resolves to a non-empty owner.

# Default owner for everything not matched more specifically below.
*                               @ctlplne/security

# --- Security-critical: the root of trust (TEST-006) ------------------------
# A compromise of any of these is, per CLAUDE.md, "the company is over." They get
# explicit, mandatory ownership so no change lands without a security review.

# AN-3 — the sole cryptography boundary. Nothing else may import crypto/*.
/internal/crypto/                @ctlplne/security

# AN-4 — the isolated signing service (private-key operations) and its gRPC wire
# contract (internal/signing/proto — the boundary to the most sensitive process).
/internal/signing/               @ctlplne/security
/internal/signing/proto/         @ctlplne/security
/cmd/trstctl-signer/            @ctlplne/security

# AN-1 — multi-tenant storage, RLS policies, and migrations.
/internal/store/                 @ctlplne/security

# The architecture linter that enforces AN-1/AN-3/AN-5/AN-8 in CI — weakening it
# silently weakens every guardrail, so it is owned alongside the crypto/signer/store.
/tools/trstctllint/             @ctlplne/security

# --- Security & supply-chain process surfaces -------------------------------
# CI/release pipelines, the security policy, and the disclosure docs gate what ships
# and how, so they carry explicit ownership too.
/.github/                        @ctlplne/security
/.github/workflows/              @ctlplne/security
/.github/CODEOWNERS              @ctlplne/security
/SECURITY.md                     @ctlplne/security
/deploy/                         @ctlplne/security
